/* PasstheEPPP — Question Bank Batch 45
   90 new questions — Ethics, Clinical, Treatment, Assessment heavy */
(function(){
    if (typeof EPPPData === 'undefined') return;

    const batch45 = [
        // === Ethics (15) ===
        {domainId:8, q:"A psychologist learns their client is HIV-positive and engaging in unprotected sex without disclosing to partners. The psychologist should:", options:["Immediately breach confidentiality to notify all identifiable sexual partners of the imminent medical risk","Assess the situation, encourage disclosure, and consult applicable laws regarding permissive disclosure to at-risk third parties","Maintain strict confidentiality as HIV status is legally protected health information under federal privacy regulations","Terminate therapy immediately and refer the client to an infectious disease specialist for further medical counseling"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) No universal rule exists for HIV. APA Policy: encourage client disclosure first. If the client refuses, some states allow (not require) limited disclosure to identifiable partners at risk. The psychologist must know their jurisdiction's laws and consult.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Immediately notifying without assessment or consultation is premature and potentially illegal.\n(C) Confidentiality has limits; some jurisdictions provide a permissive duty to warn at-risk partners.\n(D) Termination doesn't address the safety concern and constitutes abandonment."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The APA Ethics Code applies to:", options:["Exclusively to clinical and counseling psychologists engaged in direct psychological assessment and psychotherapy","All APA members and student affiliates across their diverse professional, scientific, and educational roles","Only to researchers and academicians who are actively publishing empirical studies or securing federal grant funding","Exclusively to independently licensed psychologists operating within private practice clinical settings"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) The Ethics Code applies to ALL APA members regardless of specialty — clinical, research, industrial-organizational, academic, forensic — in their work-related activities. It also applies to students.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (C), (D) The Code applies broadly to all psychology professionals in any work-related capacity, not limited to a single specialty or work environment."},
        {domainId:8, q:"A client requests access to their raw test data. Under APA ethics:", options:["Raw psychological data and testing protocols must remain strictly confidential and never be shared with clients","Psychologists generally provide test data to the client or their designee, consistent with law, unless release causes substantial harm","Only legally retained attorneys or court-appointed representatives can request and receive raw psychological testing data","Test data is automatically destroyed following the completion of the psychological report to protect proprietary test security"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Standard 9.04: psychologists provide test data (scores, responses, notes) to clients or their designees upon request, unless release would cause substantial harm. Test materials (actual test items) may be withheld to protect test security.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Clients generally have a fundamental right to access their own health data.\n(C) Clients themselves can request their data directly without legal representation.\n(D) Records must be explicitly retained for seven years per APA record-keeping guidelines."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Ethical decision-making models typically include all of the following core components EXCEPT:", options:["Identifying the primary ethical conflict and reviewing all relevant clinical and situational parameters","Consulting relevant state laws, APA ethical guidelines, and specialized professional practice standards","Resolving the dilemma based solely on the clinician’s intuitive moral compass without seeking external consultation","Considering the potential consequences of various interventions on all relevant stakeholders involved"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (C) Ethical decision-making models (e.g., Koocher & Keith-Spiegel) require objective analysis, consultation with codes/laws/colleagues, and evaluating consequences. Relying purely on subjective personal feelings or intuition without consultation is insufficient.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (B), (D) These represent standard, critical components of comprehensive ethical decision-making frameworks."},
        {domainId:8, q:"When providing telepsychology services, current ethical guidelines require psychologists to:", options:["Disregard out-of-state licensing laws assuming the services are delivered virtually through the internet","Ensure technological competence, obtain specialized informed consent, and comply with laws in both relevant jurisdictions","Restrict their telehealth clinical practice exclusively to clients residing within their primary state of residence","Utilize any readily available commercial video platform without conducting a formal HIPAA compliance assessment"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Telepsychology Guidelines require competence in the specific technology, informed consent detailing privacy risks/limitations, adherence to jurisdictional laws (where both provider and client sit), and use of secure platforms.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Licensing laws absolutely apply across state lines depending on the client's physical location.\n(C) PSYPACT and temporary practice provisions ethically allow practice across state lines under strict conditions.\n(D) Using unencrypted or non-HIPAA compliant platforms violates privacy and confidentiality standards."},
        {domainId:8, q:"When a psychologist is involved in a child custody case, the Specialty Guidelines clearly recommend:", options:["Serving simultaneously as both the treating therapist and the objective custody evaluator to ensure comprehensive data collection","Maintaining a clear professional role boundary — committing to either the evaluator role OR the therapist role, but not both","Prioritizing the recommendation of joint legal custody to promote developmental stability for the children involved","Restricting expert testimony to advocate exclusively for the specific parent who financed the psychological evaluation"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Role clarity is essential. Serving as both therapist and evaluator creates a problematic dual role — the supportive therapeutic alliance directly conflicts with the objective, neutral stance required for a forensic evaluator. Pick one role and maintain boundaries.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Dual roles create severe conflicts of interest and compromise objectivity.\n(C) Custody recommendations must be individualized and evidence-based, not based on predetermined blanket policies.\n(D) Evaluators must remain fiercely impartial regardless of who pays the fee."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Continuing education (CE) requirements required by state licensing boards exist primarily to:", options:["Generate administrative revenue for approved continuing education sponsors and state licensing agencies","Ensure psychologists systematically maintain and update their professional competence throughout their careers","Provide a mechanism to discipline or penalize psychologists who have committed prior ethical violations","Fulfill bureaucratic legislative requirements without meaningfully impacting actual clinical practice standards"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) CE requirements ensure psychologists stay current with evolving clinical science, evidence-based practice guidelines, and ethical standards. Most licensing boards require 20-40 CE hours per renewal cycle to protect the public through competence maintenance.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Revenue generation is entirely incidental to the core purpose of maintaining clinical competence.\n(C) CE is proactive competence maintenance and development, not a punitive or disciplinary measure.\n(D) CE serves a genuine, measurable professional development function essential for public safety."},
        {domainId:8, q:"A psychologist conducting an empirical research study discovers a participant shows imminent signs of suicidal ideation. The researcher should:", options:["Maintain standardized experimental protocols to ensure the integrity of the collected research data","Pause the study protocol immediately to assess risk and provide necessary clinical resources and referrals","Exclude the distressed participant's results from the final dataset without intervening clinically","Ignore the clinical presentation since the relationship is strictly experimental and not therapeutic"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Standard 8.04: researchers must address unanticipated harmful effects. Participant welfare always takes priority over data collection. The researcher must stop, assess safety, provide appropriate resources, and document the intervention.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Continuing experimental procedures when a participant is at acute risk constitutes ethical negligence.\n(C) Excluding data is secondary; failing to intervene clinically violates the fundamental principle of Beneficence.\n(D) Ethical obligations to protect human welfare extend to all professional roles, including research."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Psychologists who wish to publish detailed clinical case studies in academic journals must:", options:["Include all verbatim identifying details to ensure the clinical narrative is perfectly accurate and replicable","Sufficiently disguise the client's identity or obtain explicit written consent to protect confidentiality","Restrict case study publications exclusively to historical cases where the client is deceased","Refrain from utilizing single-subject case studies entirely due to inherent privacy constraints"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Standard 4.07: case studies require either explicit written consent from the client or sufficient disguise to prevent identification. Non-essential details (name, exact age, specific occupation) can be modified while preserving the core clinical relevance.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Presenting identifying details without consent is a severe breach of confidentiality.\n(C) Living clients can absolutely consent to publication, and their disguised cases can be ethically published.\n(D) Case studies remain a highly valuable educational and scientific tool when handled ethically."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The Belmont Report established three core ethical principles governing research with human subjects:", options:["Confidentiality, social justice, and procedural fairness","Respect for persons, beneficence, and justice","Individual autonomy, absolute veracity, and professional fidelity","Scientific honesty, methodological integrity, and public transparency"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Belmont Report (1979): (1) Respect for Persons (informed consent, protecting those with diminished autonomy), (2) Beneficence (maximize benefits, minimize harm), (3) Justice (fair distribution of research burdens and benefits).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (C), (D) While these are important ethical concepts drawn from various codes (like the APA code), they are not the specific foundational triad established by the Belmont Report."},
        {domainId:8, q:"According to the APA Ethics Code, fee-splitting arrangements in psychological practice are:", options:["Universally acceptable as long as both parties are licensed healthcare professionals","Acceptable only when the division is based on services actually provided, rather than merely for the referral","Mandatory within all multidisciplinary group practices sharing overhead expenses","Strictly illegal and unethical across all jurisdictions and practice settings"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Standard 6.07: psychologists do not pay or receive payment simply for referrals (kickbacks). Fee-splitting is acceptable only when it reflects services actually rendered (e.g., within a group practice where a clinic provides billing, office space, or administrative support).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Paying for referrals is always unethical, regardless of licensure status.\n(C) Fee arrangements in group practices must be based on proportionate services provided, not strictly mandated.\n(D) Fee-splitting based on administrative or clinical services provided is ethical; compensating purely for referrals is not."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Under current APA ethical standards, engaging in sexual intimacies with former therapy clients:", options:["Is universally acceptable provided that the formal therapeutic relationship was officially terminated","Is prohibited for at least two years post-termination, and even then, is only acceptable under the most unusual circumstances","Is explicitly prohibited under any circumstances regardless of how much time has passed","Is ethically permissible immediately after termination if the therapy was brief and supportive"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Standard 10.08: sexual relationships with former clients are prohibited for at least 2 years following cessation of therapy. Even after 2 years, psychologists bear the heavy burden of demonstrating no exploitation occurred, making it very rarely justifiable.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) A strict two-year minimum prohibition exists universally.\n(C) The standard technically permits it after two years with rigorous justification, though some state laws may ban it entirely in perpetuity.\n(D) Immediate involvement after termination is unequivocally prohibited and highly exploitative."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Institutional Review Boards (IRBs) primarily function to:", options:["Secure necessary grant funding and financial resources for institutional research operations","Review research proposals to ensure the adequate ethical protection and welfare of human participants","Peer-review and publish completed empirical findings in high-impact academic journals","Directly conduct clinical trials on behalf of major pharmaceutical organizations"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) IRBs review research involving human participants to actively ensure: adequate informed consent, appropriate risk-benefit ratios, equitable subject selection, data confidentiality protections, and additional safeguards for vulnerable populations (e.g., children, prisoners).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Funding agencies (like NIH or NSF) are responsible for funding research.\n(C) Academic journals and peer-reviewers handle the publication of research findings.\n(D) Primary investigators and research teams conduct the clinical trials; IRBs solely provide ethical oversight."},
        {domainId:8, q:"Forensic psychologists tasked with conducting court-ordered evaluations must ensure examinees understand that:", options:["All disclosed information remains strictly protected by traditional doctor-patient confidentiality privilege","The evaluation does not constitute a therapeutic relationship and findings will be shared with the retaining party or court","They possess the absolute right to refuse compliance with any question without facing legal repercussions","Their participation in the evaluation is entirely voluntary regardless of the mandated context"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Specialty Guidelines for Forensic Psychology: examinees must understand the nature and purpose of the evaluation, exactly who will receive the results, the significant limits of confidentiality, and that the relationship is strictly evaluative, not therapeutic.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Forensic evaluations operate with entirely different confidentiality parameters than standard psychotherapy.\n(C) Refusal to participate may carry severe legal or adjudicative consequences depending on the specific court order.\n(D) Court-ordered evaluations are, by definition, not voluntary."},
        {domainId:8, q:"The APA General Principle of 'Fidelity and Responsibility' explicitly encourages psychologists to:", options:["Restrict their professional conduct exclusively to abiding by municipal and federal mandates","Establish relationships of trust, uphold professional standards, and contribute a portion of professional time for little or no compensation","Focus their ethical compliance strictly on matters regarding human subjects research methodology","Maximize practice revenue by charging the highest legally permissible fees for specialized clinical services"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) APA Principle B (Fidelity and Responsibility): establishing trust, managing conflicts of interest, contributing to the profession and community (pro bono work), upholding professional standards, and being continuously aware of one's professional responsibilities to society.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Fidelity represents an aspirational ethical ideal going far beyond mere legal compliance.\n(C) Fidelity applies universally to all professional psychological roles, not exclusively research.\n(D) Setting reasonable and transparent fee practices aligns with Justice, whereas profit maximization contradicts pro bono ideals."},


        // === Clinical (20) ===
        {domainId:7, q:"Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD) was added to DSM-5 as:", options:["An unspecified V-code condition requiring further clinical study before official inclusion","A full Depressive Disorder requiring prospective daily ratings to confirm symptom timing","A specialized personality disorder characterized by cyclical emotional dysregulation","A substance-induced or medication-induced physiological manifestation of hormonal changes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) PMDD was elevated to a full Depressive Disorder in DSM-5. Requires 5+ symptoms in the premenstrual phase (mood lability, irritability, depressed mood, anxiety) with significant distress/impairment, confirmed by 2 months of prospective charting.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It was a condition for further study in DSM-IV but promoted to a full disorder in DSM-5.\n(C) PMDD is a mood disorder, not a personality disorder like BPD.\n(D) PMDD is a primary psychiatric condition, not a substance-induced disorder."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Schizoid Personality Disorder is characterized by:", options:["A pervasive pattern of excessive emotionality and attention-seeking behavior in social contexts","A pervasive pattern of detachment from social relationships and restricted emotional expression","A pervasive pattern of suspiciousness and deep distrust regarding the motives of others","A pervasive pattern of impulsivity, unstable interpersonal relationships, and fear of abandonment"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Schizoid PD: detachment from social relationships, preference for solitary activities, limited emotional expression (appears cold/flat), few close relationships, and little interest in sexual experiences. Different from schizotypal (which adds odd beliefs/perceptions).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Dramatic/attention-seeking expression characterizes Histrionic PD.\n(C) Suspiciousness and distrust characterizes Paranoid PD.\n(D) Impulsivity and instability characterize Borderline PD."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Narcissistic Personality Disorder involves:", options:["Pervasive social anxiety and extreme hypersensitivity to negative evaluation or rejection","A grandiose sense of self-importance, need for admiration, and lack of clinical empathy","Excessive preoccupation with orderliness, perfectionism, and interpersonal control","Pervasive submissive, clinging behavior driven by an excessive need to be taken care of"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) NPD: grandiosity (in fantasy or behavior), need for excessive admiration, sense of entitlement, exploits others, lacks empathy, envious, arrogant. Underlying fragile self-esteem makes them highly sensitive to criticism.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Social anxiety describes Avoidant PD or Social Anxiety Disorder.\n(C) Orderliness and perfectionism describe Obsessive-Compulsive PD.\n(D) Clingy, submissive behavior describes Dependent PD."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Depersonalization/Derealization Disorder involves:", options:["The sudden, localized inability to recall critical autobiographical information or trauma","Persistent experiences of detachment from one's own mental processes, body, or surroundings","The presence of prominent auditory or visual hallucinations perceived as originating externally","The existence of two or more distinct personality states alternating executive control"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Depersonalization: feeling detached from self, as if observing from outside, robot-like. Derealization: surroundings feel unreal, dreamlike, distorted. Reality testing remains intact (the person knows it's a subjective experience).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) This describes Dissociative Amnesia.\n(C) Hallucinations are psychotic phenomena, whereas this disorder features intact reality testing.\n(D) Distinct identity states characterize Dissociative Identity Disorder (DID)."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Reactive Attachment Disorder (RAD) is caused by:", options:["A strong, heritable genetic predisposition toward emotional dysregulation and social withdrawal","Severely inadequate care (neglect, deprivation, repeated changes of caregivers) in early childhood","Excessive parental enmeshment and overprotection during the critical toddler developmental phases","Normal developmental variations in temperament exacerbated by minor psychosocial stressors"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) RAD results from a pattern of insufficient care: social neglect, deprivation, repeated changes in primary caregivers (foster care), or rearing in institutions with high child-to-caregiver ratios. The child fails to develop normal attachment behavior.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While temperament plays a role, the core etiology defined by the DSM is environmental deprivation.\n(C) Enmeshment/overparenting does not cause the profound inability to attach seen in RAD.\n(D) RAD represents a pathological response to extreme deficits, not a normal variation."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The 'p factor' (Caspi & Moffitt) in psychopathology refers to:", options:["The placebo effect variable, which accounts for the majority of variance in treatment outcomes","A general factor underlying the shared biological and environmental liability to all psychopathology","A specific personality factor that predicts the likelihood of developing Cluster B personality disorders","A parental involvement factor that buffers against the development of severe childhood psychopathology"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) The p factor: research suggests a general psychopathology factor underlies all mental disorders, explaining their high comorbidity. Higher p = greater liability to any disorder, more severe/persistent symptoms, and worse life outcomes. Analogous to 'g' in intelligence.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The placebo effect is a treatment research concept unrelated to the p factor.\n(C) It is a general liability factor, not restricted to personality pathology.\n(D) It refers to psychopathology liability itself, not a protective parenting variable."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The dopamine hypothesis of schizophrenia proposes:", options:["A widespread deficiency in dopamine transmission directly causes the primary negative symptoms","Excessive dopamine activity in the mesolimbic pathway contributes heavily to positive symptoms","Dopamine levels are highly erratic but generally irrelevant to the core etiology of schizophrenia","An overabundance of serotonin downregulates dopamine, triggering acute psychotic brief episodes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Dopamine hypothesis: hyperactive dopamine transmission in the mesolimbic pathway → positive symptoms. Hypoactive dopamine in the mesocortical pathway → negative and cognitive symptoms. Supported by: antipsychotics block D2; amphetamines (increase DA) can cause psychosis.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It is excessive DA activity, not deficiency, that drives the hallmark positive symptoms.\n(C) Dopamine plays a central, thoroughly documented role in the disorder's pharmacology.\n(D) While serotonin is involved (especially in atypical antipsychotic mechanisms), primary etiology focuses on DA."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Trichotillomania (Hair-Pulling Disorder) is classified under:", options:["The generalized Anxiety Disorders classification due to its symptom exacerbation under acute stress","Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Disorders due to the repetitive, ritualistic behavioral features","The Disruptive, Impulse-Control, and Conduct Disorders chapter alongside pyromania and kleptomania","The Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorders category, usually as a specifier for chronic PTSD"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) DSM-5 classifies trichotillomania with OCD-related disorders (alongside OCD, BDD, hoarding, and excoriation) due to repetitive behavior features. Previously classified under Impulse Control Disorders in DSM-IV.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It was moved out of anxiety spectrum classifications due to differing neurobiology.\n(C) While it involves impulse control, DSM-5 specifically moved it to the OCD-related chapter.\n(D) It is not classified as a trauma response disorder."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Obsessive-Compulsive Personality Disorder (OCPD) is characterized by:", options:["The presence of true, ego-dystonic obsessions and compulsions that consume significant daily time","A pervasive pattern of preoccupation with orderliness, perfectionism, and control lacking flexibility","Dramatic, attention-seeking emotional displays intended to manipulate interpersonal relationships","Severe social withdrawal, restricted affect, and a pronounced lack of interest in close relationships"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) OCPD: rigid perfectionism, excessive orderliness, miserliness, inability to delegate, workaholism, stubbornness. Unlike OCD, OCPD traits are ego-syntonic (the person views them as desirable/rational). Most common personality disorder.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) True obsessions and compulsions indicate OCD, not OCPD.\n(C) Dramatic manipulation describes Histrionic or Borderline PD.\n(D) Social withdrawal describes Schizoid PD."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Dissociative Amnesia can include:", options:["Exclusively localized amnesia restricting the recall of only highly specific, isolated traumatic events","Localized, selective, generalized, or continuous amnesia, potentially paired with dissociative fugue","Exclusively the psychogenic inability to recall one's name or fundamental identity information","Only persistent retrograde amnesia resulting directly from a documented traumatic brain injury"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Types: Localized (specific event/time), Selective (some events from a period), Generalized (entire life history — rare), Continuous (ongoing inability to form new memories). Dissociative fugue (sudden travel with identity confusion) is now a specifier.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multiple broader subtypes exist well beyond just localized amnesia.\n(C) Forgetting one's essential identity is characteristic of generalized amnesia, which is the rarest form.\n(D) Dissociative amnesia is strictly psychogenic, not neurological (which would be an NCD or medical condition)."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Intermittent Explosive Disorder is characterized by:", options:["Persistent, highly irritable low mood persisting between acute episodes of aggressive outbursts","Recurrent, impulsive behavioral outbursts of disproportionate aggression not purposefully premeditated","Pervasive and excessive anxiety prompting aggressive verbal responses when the individual feels trapped","Disruptive eating behaviors immediately preceding extreme displays of physical or verbal aggression"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) IED: recurrent outbursts of disproportionate aggressive behavior (verbal or physical) that are impulsive (not premeditated), cause distress/impairment, and are not better explained by another disorder or a medical condition. Between episodes, mood is generally normal.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) A persistently irritable mood between outbursts describes Disruptive Mood Dysregulation Disorder (DMDD).\n(C) This describes anxiety-driven reactivity, not the distinct impulsivity of IED.\n(D) Eating behaviors are not a diagnostic component of IED."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The prevalence of schizophrenia across cultures is approximately:", options:["Nearly 10% of the general population due to broadening diagnostic criteria in the latest DSM revision","Roughly 1% of the population worldwide, maintaining relative consistency across diverse demographics","Less than 0.01% of the population, classifying it strictly as a rare orphan psychiatric condition","Over 20% of the population when accounting for sub-threshold schizotypal personality traits"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Schizophrenia: ~1% lifetime prevalence worldwide, relatively consistent across cultures and countries. Equal prevalence in males and females, though males have earlier onset (late teens-early 20s vs. late 20s-early 30s for females).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) 10% drastically overestimates the prevalence.\n(C) 0.01% drastically underestimates the prevalence.\n(D) 20% is incorrect; even including the broader schizophrenia spectrum, prevalence is much lower."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Somatic symptom disorders were previously grouped under:", options:["The broader Anxiety Disorders category in DSM-IV due to the presence of pervasive health worry","Somatoform Disorders in DSM-IV before being reorganized and clarified in the DSM-5 criteria","Psychotic Disorders, as patients frequently maintained delusional beliefs regarding their biology","Personality Disorders, given the chronic, intractable nature of the somatic symptom presentation"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) DSM-IV 'Somatoform Disorders' (somatization disorder, conversion disorder, hypochondriasis, pain disorder, body dysmorphic disorder) were reorganized in DSM-5 as Somatic Symptom and Related Disorders — with BDD moved to OCD-related.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While health anxiety is present, they formed their own distinct Somatoform category.\n(C) They are not classified as psychotic; reality testing regarding the world remains intact.\n(D) They are clinical syndrome (Axis I) conditions, not personality traits."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Kleptomania is classified under:", options:["Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Disorders due to the compulsive nature of the stealing behavior","Disruptive, Impulse-Control, and Conduct Disorders alongside conditions like pyromania and ODD","Anxiety Disorders, as the theft serves primarily to relieve intense, overwhelming social anxiety","Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders due to its neurobiological similarity to behavioral addictions"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Kleptomania is in the Impulse Control chapter alongside IED, pyromania, conduct disorder, and ODD. Characterized by recurrent failure to resist urges to steal objects not needed for personal use or monetary value.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While it involves compulsions, it remained in Impulse-Control rather than moving to the OCD spectrum.\n(C) The primary mechanism is impulse failure, not anxiety relief.\n(D) Unlike Gambling Disorder, Kleptomania was not moved to the Addictive Disorders category."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Late-onset schizophrenia (after age 40) is:", options:["Clinically impossible according to the DSM-5, as schizophrenia must onset during late adolescence","Possible, more common in women, and frequently presents with prominent paranoid delusional themes","Identical to early-onset presentations in all clinical respects, differing solely in the age of onset","Overwhelmingly caused by chronic substance use rather than being a primary psychotic disorder"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Late-onset schizophrenia (after 40) and very-late-onset (after 60) occur, disproportionately in women. Features: more paranoid ideation, auditory hallucinations, better premorbid functioning, fewer negative symptoms compared to early-onset.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While peak onset is late teens-early 30s, later onset is formally recognized.\n(C) Late-onset has distinct clinical features (e.g., fewer negative symptoms, better premorbid function).\n(D) It is a primary psychotic disorder, though substance-induced psychosis must be ruled out."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Neurodevelopmental disorders in DSM-5 include all EXCEPT:", options:["Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder, which deeply impacts executive functioning development","Autism Spectrum Disorder, characterized by social deficits and restricted or repetitive behaviors","Major Depressive Disorder, early-onset subtype characterized by severe emotional dysregulation","Specific Learning Disorder, involving significant difficulties in reading, writing, or mathematics"], answer:2, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (C) MDD is a Depressive Disorder, not a neurodevelopmental disorder. The Neurodevelopmental chapter includes: Intellectual Disability, Communication Disorders, ASD, ADHD, Specific Learning Disorder, Motor Disorders (including Tic Disorders).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (B), (D) These are all classic Neurodevelopmental Disorders listed in that specific DSM-5 chapter."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Social (Pragmatic) Communication Disorder, new in DSM-5, involves:", options:["The complete global absence of functional expressive language despite intact receptive comprehension","Difficulties with the social use of verbal/nonverbal communication without the restricted behaviors of ASD","Profound articulation problems that render speech generally unintelligible to familiar listeners","A severe presentation of selective mutism driven by situational anxiety rather than skill deficits"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) SCD: persistent difficulties with social use of communication — understanding context, following conversational rules, adjusting communication to the listener, using nonverbal cues. Distinguished from ASD by the ABSENCE of restricted/repetitive behaviors.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Language mechanics and vocabulary may be perfectly intact; the issue is pragmatic/social use.\n(C) Articulation issues describe a Speech Sound Disorder.\n(D) Selective Mutism involves an emotional refusal/inability to speak, whereas SCD is a pervasive pragmatic skill deficit."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Gambling Disorder is now classified under:", options:["The revised Disruptive, Impulse-Control, and Conduct Disorders category reflecting poor self-regulation","Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders due to shared neurobiological reward system activation","The Personality Disorders cluster reflecting a pervasive pattern of reckless and impulsive traits","The Anxiety Disorders spectrum, as gambling acts to temporarily relieve persistent generalized worry"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) DSM-5 moved Gambling Disorder from Impulse Control (DSM-IV: Pathological Gambling) to Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders based on neuroscience showing similar reward system involvement. It's the only recognized behavioral addiction in DSM-5.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) It was explicitly removed from the Impulse Control category in DSM-5.\n(C) It is an Axis I clinical syndrome, not a pervasive personality disorder.\n(D) The primary mechanism involves dopamine reward systems, not anxiety relief."},
        {domainId:7, q:"Encopresis is:", options:["The involuntary nighttime voiding of urine commonly referred to as nocturnal bedwetting","The repeated passage of feces into inappropriate places after age 4, not due to a medical condition","A severe substance use disorder characterized by the ingestion of toxic non-food items","An eating disorder involving the repeated regurgitation and re-chewing of recently ingested food"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Encopresis: repeated defecation in inappropriate places (clothing, floor) at least once monthly for 3+ months, in a child chronologically or developmentally ≥4 years, not due to a medical condition. Subtypes: with or without constipation/overflow incontinence.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Bedwetting is defined diagnostically as Enuresis.\n(C) Eating non-food items is defined as Pica.\n(D) Regurgitating food is defined as Rumination Disorder."},
        {domainId:7, q:"The protective factors against suicide include:", options:["Unrestricted access to lethal means paired with a history of profound environmental instability","Strong social connections, effective clinical treatment, problem-solving skills, and reasons for living","A pervasive sense of psychological hopelessness regarding the possibility of improving one's future","A history of multiple previous suicide attempts demonstrating a high tolerance for physical self-harm"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Protective factors buffer against risk: strong relationships, access to effective treatment, cultural beliefs discouraging suicide, problem-solving skills, children in the home, sense of purpose.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Access to lethal means is a prominent, severe RISK factor.\n(C) Hopelessness (as measured by the Beck Hopelessness Scale) is a highly potent RISK factor.\n(D) Previous attempts are the single strongest statistical RISK factor for completed suicide."},

        // === Treatment (15) ===
        {domainId:6, q:"The difference between positive and negative punishment is:", options:["Positive punishment always yields prosocial outcomes, whereas negative punishment produces defiance","Positive punishment adds an aversive stimulus; negative punishment removes a desired stimulus","Positive punishment increases the target behavior by providing intermittent social reinforcement","They are functionally identical paradigms that extinguish behaviors via strict classical conditioning"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Positive punishment: ADD something unpleasant (spanking, criticism) → behavior decreases. Negative punishment: REMOVE something pleasant (loss of privileges, time-out from reinforcement) → behavior decreases. 'Positive/negative' = add/remove, not good/bad.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Positive/negative refer to adding/removing, not moral quality.\n(C) ALL punishment decreases behavior by definition, whereas reinforcement increases it.\n(D) They use different operant mechanisms (addition vs. removal) to reduce behavior."},
        {domainId:6, q:"In Minuchin's structural family therapy, 'enactment' refers to:", options:["Assuming the role of another family member to build cross-generational psychological empathy","Asking family members to interact with each other in session so the therapist can observe real-time patterns","Writing a detailed genogram and family history narrative to trace emotional cutoffs across generations","Conducting individual psychodynamic therapy concurrently alongside structural family interventions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Enactment: the therapist asks family members to discuss or transact a problem directly with each other IN SESSION rather than just describing it. This allows direct observation of interaction patterns, boundaries, and hierarchies for real-time intervention.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Role-reversal is a psychodramatic or Gestalt technique.\n(C) Genograms and multigenerational history characterize Bowenian therapy.\n(D) Enactment specifically involves family interaction, not individual psychodynamic work."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Reciprocal inhibition (Wolpe) is based on the principle that:", options:["Two distinct clinical anxiety disorders can coexist and amplify one another in systemic phobias","An anxiety response can be weakened by a simultaneous response that is incompatible with anxiety","Anxiety always intensifies dramatically before extinguishing completely during flooding exposure","Only psychotropic medication acting on the GABA receptor can effectively reduce physiological terror"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Reciprocal inhibition: if a response incompatible with anxiety (deep relaxation, feeding, assertive behavior) occurs in the presence of the feared stimulus, the anxiety response is weakened. Foundation of systematic desensitization.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The principle states they CANNOT coexist — one physically inhibits the other.\n(C) While anxiety spikes in flooding, reciprocal inhibition relies on explicitly preventing anxiety via a competing response.\n(D) Reciprocal inhibition is a foundational behavioral, non-pharmacological principle."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Strategic family therapy (Haley, Madanes) focuses on:", options:["Exploring family emotional history and differentiation of self across three or more generations","Changing specific problem behaviors using directives, paradoxical interventions, and restructuring logic","Resolving internal, unconscious individual psychodynamics projected onto the family system unit","The exclusive use of psychotropic medication to stabilize the identified patient's symptomatology"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Strategic therapy: problem-focused, brief, directive. The therapist designs specific interventions (directives, paradoxical techniques, prescribing the symptom) targeting the problem and the interactional sequences maintaining it. Symptoms are viewed as serving a function.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Multigenerational focus describes Bowenian Family Therapy.\n(C) Focusing on unconscious projections describes Object Relations Family Therapy.\n(D) Strategic therapy is a systemic psychological approach, not pharmacotherapy."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Cognitive defusion in ACT refers to:", options:["Merging disparate cognitive schemas to create a singular, unified narrative of the self-concept","Learning to observe thoughts as mental events rather than literal truths, reducing their behavioral power","Systematically increasing emotional entanglement with thoughts until a therapeutic catharsis is reached","Attempting to aggressively eliminate, suppress, or permanently alter maladaptive cognitive content"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Defusion (deliteralization): changing the RELATIONSHIP to thoughts without changing content. Techniques: 'I notice I'm having the thought that...', singing the thought, repeating it until it loses meaning. Creates distance between the person and their thoughts.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Defusion is the opposite of fusion (getting entangled with thoughts).\n(C) ACT aims to comprehensively DECREASE cognitive fusion, not increase it.\n(D) ACT explicitly avoids thought suppression, contrasting with traditional CBT's cognitive restructuring."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Play therapy in pediatric clinical settings is most developmentally appropriate for:", options:["Adults suffering from profound neurocognitive disorders requiring non-verbal expressive outlets","Children who lack the verbal skills to express feelings directly, using play as the fundamental medium","Adolescents actively rebelling against traditional cognitive-behavioral conversational therapy models","Exclusively for children formally diagnosed with Autism Spectrum Disorder requiring sensory management"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Play therapy: play is children's natural language. Through play, children express emotions, process experiences, and develop coping skills. Directive (therapist structures play) or non-directive (child-led, as in Child-Centered Play Therapy based on Rogers).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) While occasionally adapted, play therapy was systematically developed for pediatric populations.\n(C) Adolescents typically transition to 'talk therapy' or specific expressive arts rather than early childhood play.\n(D) It is a broad, universal modality, not restricted solely to ASD populations."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Operant conditioning primarily differs from classical conditioning in that operant conditioning:", options:["Centers exclusively on involuntary reflexive responses elicited by unconditioned stimuli","Focuses on how the consequences of voluntary behavior strengthen or weaken the future probability","Is a highly theoretical concept developed primarily by Ivan Pavlov studying canine digestion","Relies entirely on antecedent environmental pairing rather than active environmental consequences"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Operant (Skinner): voluntary behavior shaped by consequences (reinforcement increases, punishment decreases). Classical (Pavlov): involuntary responses learned through stimulus associations. Key distinction: voluntary vs. involuntary, consequences vs. stimulus pairing.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Involuntary, reflexive responses define classical conditioning.\n(C) Pavlov discovered classical conditioning; Skinner formulated operant conditioning.\n(D) Operant relies heavily on consequences (post-behavior), not merely antecedent pairing before behavior."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The therapeutic window for trauma processing refers to:", options:["A restrictive 45-minute clinical time frame during which traumatic memories must be fully resolved","The optimal emotional arousal level where processing is effective—neither avoidant nor overwhelmed","An adjunctive visual technique where clients imagine a physical window to escape flashback triggers","The brief period immediately following an assault required by insurance for acute stress interventions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Therapeutic window (Briere) / Window of Tolerance (Ogden/Siegel): the client must be emotionally engaged enough to process the trauma (avoiding dissociation/numbing) but not so overwhelmed that they cannot integrate the experience. The therapist titrates exposure to maintain this optimal zone.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (C), (D) These are fabricated distractors entirely unrelated to the established clinical concept of arousal modulation."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Assertiveness training systematically teaches clients how to:", options:["Adopt a dominant, aggressive conversational posture to ensure personal boundaries are heavily defended","Express their needs, rights, and feelings directly and honestly while respecting the rights of others","Revert to a passive, highly deferential interaction style to de-escalate extreme interpersonal conflicts","Utilize covert psychological manipulation to subtly coerce peers into fulfilling interpersonal demands"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Assertiveness: the middle ground between passive (suppressing needs) and aggressive (violating others' rights). Includes: making requests, saying no, expressing feelings, giving/receiving compliments, and managing conflict constructively.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Assertiveness distinctly differs from aggression, which frequently violates others' boundaries.\n(C) Passivity is precisely the maladaptive interaction style that assertiveness training attempts to remediate.\n(D) Assertiveness is inherently honest, transparent, and direct—fundamentally opposing manipulation."},
        {domainId:6, q:"In group therapy, Yalom identified 11 therapeutic factors. Which is generally considered MOST important by group members across studies?", options:["Direct didactic guidance and formal instruction delivered unilaterally by the group facilitator","Interpersonal learning via observing how one affects others and experimenting with novel behaviors","The instillations of profound psychological hope occurring uniquely during the first clinical session","The structured imparting of standardized psychoeducational information regarding shared diagnoses"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Interpersonal learning: members receive feedback about how they affect others (input) and experiment with new behaviors in the safety of the group (output). The group becomes a social microcosm for corrective emotional experiences. It consistently ranks highest in member surveys.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (C), (D) All are valid clinical factors identified by Yalom, but interpersonal learning is consistently identified by members in mature groups as the central mechanism of change."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Sensate focus exercises are primarily used in clinical practice during:", options:["Severe depression treatment protocols focusing heavily on rigorous behavioral activation scheduling","Sex therapy frameworks resolving performance anxiety through graduated, non-demand pleasuring","Prolonged Exposure therapy for combat-related PTSD aiming to reintroduce generalized somatic signals","Cognitive-behavioral anger management aimed at mapping physiological escalation during acute disputes"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Sensate focus (Masters & Johnson): couples take turns touching/being touched in graduated steps (initially non-genital, then genital), focusing on sensation rather than performance. Reduces performance anxiety and demand for orgasm.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Depression primarily relies on Behavioral Activation without specific graded intimate contact.\n(C) PTSD interoceptive exposure maps inner sensations but lacks the unique dyadic pleasuring component of sensate focus.\n(D) Anger management utilizes physiological autonomic monitoring, not intimate physical touching protocols."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Parent-Child Interaction Therapy (PCIT) is an empirically supported intervention featuring:", options:["Group therapy exclusively for highly distressed parents completely lacking functional parenting strategies","A live coaching model where therapists direct parents in real-time via earpiece to shape child interactions","A psychopharmacological consultation module mandating daily stimulant prescriptions for severe ADHD","A purely individual play therapy approach where the distressed child attends sessions independently of parents"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) PCIT: for children 2-7 with disruptive behavior. Two phases: Child-Directed Interaction (PRIDE skills) and Parent-Directed Interaction (effective commands). The therapist observes through a one-way mirror and provides live, in-the-moment coaching to the parent via 'bug-in-the-ear'.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) PCIT is fundamentally dyadic (treating the parent-child pair together), not a generic parent-only parenting class.\n(C) PCIT is a behavioral interactional intervention, offering no psychopharmacological or prescribing components.\n(D) Unlike Child-Centered Play Therapy alone, PCIT absolutely requires the parent's highly active, supervised participation."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Clinical biofeedback essentially involves:", options:["Receiving electronic data about internal biological processes to learn conscious, voluntary control over them","Engaging in generalized mindfulness meditation completely without the assistance of any technological monitoring","Utilizing specialized DNA genetic testing panels to precisely predict an individual's lifetime somatic risk","Undergoing intensive electroconvulsive therapy treatments to disrupt maladaptive biological neural firing patterns"], answer:0, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (A) Biofeedback: electronic monitoring provides real-time information about physiological processes (EMG for muscle tension, EEG for brainwaves, peripheral temperature). Clients utilize this feedback to learn to purposefully modulate autonomic nervous system functions.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(B) While meditation techniques can be adjunctive, biofeedback mathematically requires distinct technological measurement apparatus.\n(C) Genetic testing is an immutable diagnostic procedure offering absolutely no real-time physiological behavioral feedback loop.\n(D) ECT is an acute, passive psychiatric neurostimulation intervention distinct from conscious, active self-regulation learning."},
        {domainId:6, q:"Behavioral couples therapy for substance abuse primarily works by:", options:["Directing all clinical focus exclusively onto the intricate details of the couple's dysfunctional communication","Combining specific contingency management for abstinence with integrated relationship enhancement skills","Mandating the immediate physical separation of the emotionally enmeshed partners during the active treatment phase","Treating the addicted partner exclusively in traditional individual therapy while offering the spouse independent support"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) BCT (O'Farrell): combines substance abuse treatment (contingency contracting, daily trust discussion/sobriety contract) with relationship enhancement (communication skills, shared activities). Notably more effective than individual treatment alone for maintaining abstinence and repairing relationships.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) BCT explicitly integrates rigorous behavioral substance abuse protocols (contracts) natively alongside communication work.\n(C) BCT specifically brings partners forcefully together cooperatively to structurally combat the behavioral addiction.\n(D) BCT is inherently conjoint (defined as couples therapy); intentionally segregating them defines traditional individual therapeutic approaches."},
        {domainId:6, q:"The primary difference between efficacy and effectiveness in psychological treatment research is:", options:["They are completely synonymous methodological research terms utilized interchangeably across modern academic literature","Efficacy measures results in highly controlled settings; effectiveness measures results in real-world practice","Efficacy research validates the mechanisms of psychotropic medications, while effectiveness validates psychotherapeutic models","Effectiveness research is universally considered statistically invalid compared to the rigor of randomized efficacy trials"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Efficacy: does the treatment work under ideal, strict, controlled conditions (RCTs, manualized treatment, screened clients with no comorbidities)? Effectiveness: does it work in actual, 'messy' real-world clinical practice (diverse clients, varied training, community settings)?\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They address profoundly different fundamental dimensions of treatment generalizability and external validity.\n(C) Both terms apply appropriately and universally to both psychological therapy and pharmacological outcome research paradigms.\n(D) Effectiveness research (practice-based evidence) is highly valued practically for establishing vital external ecological validity."},

        // === Assessment (10) ===
        {domainId:5, q:"The WAIS-IV provides which primary index scores?", options:["Verbal Comprehension, Working Memory, and a singular highly-weighted General Ability Index score","Verbal Comprehension, Perceptual Reasoning, Working Memory, Processing Speed, and Full Scale IQ","Fluid Reasoning, Quantitative Reasoning, Visual-Spatial Processing, matrices, and Full Scale IQ","Verbal IQ, Performance IQ, Processing Speed, and a distinct measure of Premorbid Functioning"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) WAIS-IV indices: VCI (Verbal Comprehension), PRI (Perceptual Reasoning), WMI (Working Memory), PSI (Processing Speed), plus FSIQ. Each index contains 2-3 subtests. The WAIS-V adds a Fluid Reasoning index.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) GAI is an alternate composite, not primary.\n(C) Fluid Reasoning, Quantitative, etc., characterize the Stanford-Binet (SB5) indexes.\n(D) V-IQ/P-IQ split characterizes the older WAIS-III, not WAIS-IV."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The MMPI-2 validity scales include:", options:["The primary clinical detection scales designed exclusively for measuring severe malingering","L (Lie), F (Infrequency), K (Correction), and additional scales like VRIN, TRIN, Fb, Fp","The distinct positive impression management index and highly specific self-deception enhancement","Only a single, highly sensitive generalized consistency metric evaluating semantic contradictions"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) MMPI-2 validity scales: L (unsophisticated positive impression management), F (infrequent responding/faking bad), K (sophisticated defensiveness), VRIN (variable response inconsistency), TRIN (true response inconsistency), Fb (back-page F), Fp (psychiatric infrequency).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) They detect much more than malingering, assessing defensiveness, inconsistency, etc.\n(C) PIM and NIM are validity scales found on the PAI, not MMPI-2.\n(D) Multiple distinct validity indicators synergize to provide a comprehensive assessment."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Bayley Scales of Infant Development are designed for:", options:["School-aged children to quantitatively measure specific learning disabilities and reading delays","Infants and toddlers ages 1-42 months to assess developmental status and cognitive functioning","Extremely premature neonates in the intensive care unit to determine fundamental physiological survival","Preschool-aged children from 3-5 years to formally evaluate school readiness for public kindergarten"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Bayley-4: assesses cognitive, language (receptive/expressive), motor (fine/gross), social-emotional, and adaptive behavior development in infants/toddlers. Used to identify developmental delays and qualify for early intervention services.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A), (D) The Bayley is specifically normed for infants and toddlers under 42 months, differentiating it from WPPSI or WISC.\n(C) Bayley measures specific functional capabilities, not basic neonate survival functioning (as indexed by APGAR)."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Concurrent validity is established by:", options:["Correlating an individual's current test performance with a theoretically expected future criterion","Correlating test scores with a formally established criterion measured comprehensively at the same time","Conducting an intensive expert review panel to evaluate the fundamental face validity of the content","Calculating the rigorous internal statistical consistency of the items using Cronbach's alpha reliability"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Concurrent validity: criterion-related validity where the predictor and criterion are measured simultaneously. Example: correlating a new depression scale with an established one (BDI-II) administered at the same time. Contrasts with predictive validity (future criterion).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Future criterion correlation explicitly equals predictive validity.\n(C) Expert review fundamentally constitutes content validity.\n(D) Internal consistency explicitly equals reliability (Cronbach's alpha), not validity."},
        {domainId:5, q:"In psychological assessment, 'norms' refer to:", options:["Strictly regulated ethical standards regarding the proper administration and responsible scoring of an exam","The distribution of scores from the standardization sample used as a primary reference for interpretation","The theoretical absolute threshold distinguishing functional states from pathological psychiatric disorders","The specific qualitative behavioral boundaries explicitly mandated by governmental diagnostic entities"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Norms: the score distribution from a representative standardization sample. Individual scores are compared to norms to determine where they fall relative to the reference group (percentiles, standard scores, age/grade equivalents).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Psychometric norms are empirical statistical distributions, not behavioral moral/ethical guides.\n(C) The theoretical boundary between sick and well relies on cut-scores, but norms cover the whole distribution.\n(D) Norms are psychometric properties generated by publishers, not government regulations."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Wisconsin Card Sorting Test assesses:", options:["Verbal and nonverbal declarative memory capacity, explicitly targeting hippocampal declarative encoding","Executive function processes, specifically encompassing cognitive flexibility, set-shifting, and reasoning","Enduring personality dimensions mapped onto the comprehensive Five-Factor structural taxonomy model","Academic achievement deficits, primarily reading comprehension syntax and mathematical calculations"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) WCST: participants sort cards by rules that change without warning. Assesses the ability to form abstract concepts, shift cognitive sets, and use feedback to modify behavior. Sensitive to frontal lobe dysfunction (perseverative errors).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Explicit Memory relies on WMS or CVLT.\n(C) Personality dimensions map onto MMPI, PAI, or NEO-PI.\n(D) Academic achievement maps onto WJ, WIAT, or KTEA."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Inter-rater reliability is MOST important for:", options:["Highly structured, computerized self-report clinical symptom questionnaires like the comprehensive BDI-II","Assessment methods inherently involving subjective judgment like behavioral observations or projectives","Standardized multiple-choice academic achievement examinations featuring strictly objective answer keys","Automated neurocognitive processing speed batteries governed by rapid, sophisticated algorithmic scoring"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Inter-rater reliability matters when scoring involves judgment. Two raters observing the same behavior, scoring the same Rorschach response, or coding the same therapy session should reach similar conclusions. Measured by kappa, ICC, or percentage agreement.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Self-report questionnaires uniquely mandate objective scoring lacking observer bias.\n(C) Multiple-choice objectively eliminates active rater variance judgments.\n(D) Computerized algorithms perfectly eliminate unreliable human rater judgment variability."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Thematic Apperception Test (TAT) asks examinees to:", options:["Interpret completely ambiguous, symmetrical inkblots mapping latent, deeply unconscious impulses","Create comprehensive narrative stories about ambiguous pictures showing complex interpersonal scenes","Rapidly complete a standardized series of unfinished thematic sentences revealing immediate anxieties","Draw a detailed person, house, and tree specifically highlighting unconscious projective relational needs"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) TAT (Murray): examinees create stories (beginning, middle, end, feelings of characters) about ambiguous pictures showing people in various situations. Themes reveal needs, motives, conflicts, and interpersonal patterns through projection.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Ambiguous Inkblots comprise the Rorschach technique.\n(C) Completing designated sentences comprises the Sentence Completion Test (Rotter).\n(D) Drawing comprises the structured Draw-A-Person, or House-Tree-Person tasks."},
        {domainId:5, q:"Measurement invariance in assessment means:", options:["Statistical absolute certainty that zero measurement error structurally exists within the instrument","A given test demonstrably measures the identical theoretical construct in the exact same way across groups","Every demographic group inevitably achieves the exact identical mean raw score during administration","Only a single, highly standardized form of the measurement instrument exists globally to prevent bias"], answer:1, difficulty:"hard", rationale:"Correct: (B) Measurement invariance (factorial invariance): the test's factor structure, factor loadings, and intercepts are equivalent across groups. Without invariance, group comparisons may be invalid — score differences could reflect measurement artifact rather than true differences.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) All empirical tests invariably possess measurable statistical measurement error margins.\n(C) Diverse groups frequently achieve differing means; invariance specifies measurement parity, not score parity.\n(D) Multiple invariant equivalent test alternate forms can effectively exist logically and empirically."},
        {domainId:5, q:"The Rey Complex Figure Test assesses:", options:["Complex verbal working memory and the strategic semantic clustering of narrative story information","Visuospatial construction, strategic organizational ability, and detailed nonverbal visual memory recall","Broad personality integration parameters, primarily assessing organizational defenses against psychosis","Academic functional reading comprehension capacity alongside generalized arithmetic spatial processing"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) RCFT: examinees copy a complex geometric figure (organization, accuracy), then reproduce it from memory (immediate and delayed recall). Assesses visuospatial construction, planning/organization, and visual memory. Sensitive to right hemisphere and frontal dysfunction.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Verbal episodic memory explicitly links to CVLT or WMS Logical Memory indices.\n(C) Broad Personality organization specifically links to MMPI, PAI, or Rorschach dimensions.\n(D) Arithmetic mapping links to academic achievement batteries, not specialized neuropysch spatial structures."},

        // === Cognitive/Bio/Social (15) ===
        {domainId:2, q:"Encoding specificity (Tulving) states that:", options:["The original encoding context is fundamentally irrelevant to the probability of successful memory retrieval","Retrieval is statistically most effective when the retrieval context closely matches the encoding context","Only exclusively visual encoding stimuli can be preserved over significantly delayed retrieval intervals","Declarative episodic memory remains structurally perfect assuming complete conscious encoding focus"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Encoding specificity: cues effective at retrieval are those that were processed during encoding. If you study while sad, sad mood at test improves recall (mood-dependent memory). State-dependent learning is a related phenomenon.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Experimental context is deeply, highly relevant — the matching principle is the absolute core claim.\n(C) All encoding operational modalities routinely follow this precise contextual matching principle.\n(D) Biological memory is intrinsically reconstructive and highly fallible across time scales."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The serial position effect shows:", options:["All items within a continuous sequential list possess perfectly equal memorability across time domains","Items at the beginning (primacy effect) and end (recency effect) of an extended list are remembered best","Only items strategically positioned in the exact middle of a sequence achieve permanent consolidation","Exceedingly long qualitative verbal lists practically cannot be consciously memorized under any condition"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Primacy effect: early items are rehearsed more and transferred to LTM. Recency effect: last items are still in STM. Middle items (asymptote) are recalled worst. Delayed recall eliminates recency but preserves primacy.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The classical U-shaped recall curve graphically shows wildly unequal memorability.\n(C) Middle temporal items are statistically recalled consistently WORST.\n(D) Extended lists can be effectively memorized; sequential position drastically affects relative ease."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The Dunning-Kruger effect describes:", options:["A generalized heuristic where highly acclaimed domain experts consistently overestimate their abilities","Low-competence individuals overestimating their abilities while high-competence individuals underestimate","A phenomenon displaying perfectly equal self-assessment accuracy observed across all clinical skill levels","A rigid cognitive distortion exclusively affecting quantitative reasoning rather than interpersonal skills"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Dunning-Kruger: metacognitive failure — people with limited knowledge/skill lack the ability to recognize their limitations, leading to overestimation. Conversely, highly skilled individuals may underestimate themselves, assuming tasks easy for them are easy for everyone.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Experts routinely tend to empirically UNDERESTIMATE their relative domain abilities.\n(C) Self-assessment metacognitive accuracy radically varies systematically with overall competence level.\n(D) The persistent effect applies broadly across practically all cognitive domains."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Levels of processing theory (Craik & Lockhart) predicts:", options:["Shallow, purely structural processing reliably produces the most enduring long-term memory trace","Deeper, semantic processing focused on meaning at encoding leads to much stronger, durable memory traces","All continuous processing levels eventually produce perfectly equal semantic memory networks","Only highly intensive visual perceptual processing meaningfully contributes to procedural learning"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Levels of processing: structural (shallow — physical features), phonemic (intermediate — sound), semantic (deep — meaning). Semantic processing produces the best recall. However, transfer-appropriate processing qualifies this — depth matters most when retrieval also requires deep processing.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Specifically shallow processing invariably produces uniquely weak, fragile memory traces.\n(C) Only deeper, intentional semantic processing consistently produces robustly stronger memory links.\n(D) Multimodal semantic processing is highly relevant, far outreaching basic visual modalities."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Prospective memory refers to:", options:["Consciously remembering highly explicit autobiographical events fundamentally anchored in the distant past","Remembering to consciously perform specific intended actions at appropriate, designated times in the future","Highly specialized memory utilized exclusively for navigating complex geographical spatial locations","Completely unconscious procedural memory necessary for structurally executing highly automated behaviors"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Prospective memory: remembering to do things ('remember to call the dentist,' 'take medication at 3pm'). Time-based (at a specific time) vs. event-based (when something happens). Distinct from retrospective memory (remembering past events/facts).\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Remembering deep past events explicitly constitutes retrospective/episodic memory.\n(C) Remembering complex geographical spatial layouts involves hippocampus spatial memory.\n(D) Accessing unconscious motor loops implicitly comprises basic nondeclarative memory."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The thalamus functions primarily as:", options:["A sophisticated neuroendocrine mechanism strictly governing complex physiological hormone production","A sensory relay station primarily routing incoming sensory information to the appropriate cortical areas","The core dominant emotion center actively regulating intense fear, aggressive impulses, and basic survival","The absolute primary motor control center precisely generating highly explicit voluntary bodily movement"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) The thalamus relays all sensory information (except olfaction) to the appropriate cortical processing areas. Also involved in alertness, attention, and motor signals. Think of it as the brain's 'switchboard.'\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Core hormone production actively relies upon the structural hypothalamus and pituitary.\n(C) Primal emotional affective regulation occurs within the amygdala and limbic network.\n(D) Gross complex motor command relies upon the supplementary motor cortex and basal ganglia."},
        {domainId:1, q:"The autonomic nervous system is divided into:", options:["The structural somatic division managing movement and the overarching central nervous system processing","The sympathetic division activating fight-or-flight arousal and the parasympathetic division promoting rest","The specialized afferent neural pathways receiving signals and efferent pathways executing commands","The neurobiologically distinct dominant left cortical hemisphere and the subordinate right hemisphere"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) ANS: Sympathetic (arousal, emergency response — increases HR, dilates pupils, inhibits digestion) and Parasympathetic (calming, restoration — decreases HR, constricts pupils, promotes digestion). They generally have opposing effects.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Somatic branches remain distinct divisions of the broader PNS; CNS represents the brain/spine.\n(C) Afferent/efferent describes physiological neuronal direction, circumventing structural ANS divisions.\n(D) Lateralization describes functional neocortical divisions, disconnected from autonomic autonomic functioning."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Diffusion of responsibility in the bystander effect means:", options:["Everyone implicitly takes comprehensive personal responsibility when observing a traumatic emergency","Each bystander's subjective sense of personal obligation actively decreases as crowd magnitude increases","Civic responsibility is formally and legally assigned to specific individuals within a large social collective","Only one single isolated individual can ever practically maintain responsibility during a prolonged crisis"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Diffusion of responsibility: 'someone else will help.' With more bystanders, each individual feels less personally responsible for acting. This is a primary mechanism (along with pluralistic ignorance) explaining reduced helping in groups.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Statistically precisely the opposite — individualized core responsibility DECREASES sequentially.\n(C) In unstructured emergent chaotic emergencies, formal structural responsibility is rarely assigned effectively.\n(D) Practically all adjacent bystanders potentially help — but social diffusion reduces pressing obligation."},
        {domainId:3, q:"Learned helplessness (Seligman) theory proposes that depression can result from:", options:["Chronically experiencing far too much professional success leading to an existential identity crisis void","The deeply ingrained perception that negative outcomes are entirely uncontrollable, causing extreme passivity","Only exclusively inherited genetic biological factors completely unrelated to environmental contingencies","Consistently experiencing excessive quantities of disorganized REM sleep significantly disrupting metabolism"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Seligman: organisms exposed to inescapable aversive events learn that their behavior has no effect on outcomes → passive, depressive-like behavior even when escape becomes possible. Reformulated: attributional style (internal, stable, global attributions for negative events) mediates learned helplessness and depression.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Frequent success typically reinforces operant coping behaviors, countering subjective helplessness.\n(C) The learned helplessness empirical paradigm explicitly emphasizes specific cognitive-environmental learning conditioning.\n(D) While sleep architecture shifts within clinical depression, it fails to explain helplessness causality paradigms."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Source monitoring errors occur when:", options:["Human autobiographical memory remains structurally perfect, resisting all external qualitative distortions","A person correctly remembers information but subsequently misattributes its specific origin or context","Only pediatric populations exhibiting severe generalized delays encounter cognitive reality distortions","Informational sources are always flawlessly consciously identified regardless of the emotional intensity"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) Source monitoring (Johnson): failure to correctly attribute the source of a memory. Examples: thinking you told someone something when you only thought about it, confusing a dream with reality, false memory of reading something that was actually said. Important in eyewitness testimony.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Biological implicit memory strongly remains broadly imperfect and notably reconstructive.\n(C) Profound source monitoring cognitive errors practically occur uniformly across lifespan developmental ages.\n(D) Explicit source conceptual misattributions are robustly common across diverse experiential populations."},
        {domainId:2, q:"Emotional intelligence (Salovey & Mayer) involves:", options:["Exclusively maximizing standardized academic intelligence metrics predicting objective career dominance","Accurately perceiving, skillfully using, comprehensively understanding, and adaptively managing emotions","Chronically remaining highly emotional and explicitly dysregulated throughout all interpersonal engagements","Aggressively suppressing all subjective emotional experiences to maximize strictly logical decision-making"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) EI (four-branch model): (1) Perceiving emotions accurately, (2) Using emotions to facilitate thought, (3) Understanding emotional processes, (4) Managing emotions effectively. Predicts relationship quality, mental health, and some job performance beyond IQ.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Emotional Intelligence functions distinctly from objective standardized cognitive academic factors.\n(C) Emotional intelligence features adaptive skill-based emotional modulation, strictly avoiding volatile dysfunction.\n(D) Emotional intelligence prioritizes adaptive processing application, comprehensively avoiding harmful systematic suppression."},
        {domainId:2, q:"The availability heuristic leads people to:", options:["Exhaustively consider all available scientific evidence before formally reaching any clinical diagnosis","Judge the frequency or probability of events primarily based on how easily specific examples come to mind","Only ever purposefully utilize strict analytical, logical, deductive reasoning to solve complex estimations","Actively completely ignore and discard all highly memorable, salient, emotionally provocative occurrences"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Availability heuristic (Tversky & Kahneman): events that are easily recalled (vivid, recent, emotionally charged) are judged as more frequent/probable. After seeing news about plane crashes, people overestimate flying danger despite driving being statistically more dangerous.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) The cognitive heuristic intentionally heavily bypasses slow, meticulous empirical analytical information consideration.\n(C) Such heuristics functionally represent rapid intuitive estimations, entirely avoiding deliberate, intensive logical deduction.\n(D) Singularly vivid occurrences are explicitly inappropriately OVERWEIGHTED across heuristic algorithmic probability maps."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Attachment research shows that approximately what percentage of infants are classified as securely attached?", options:["Approximately 20-25%, actively reflecting a significantly high baseline of defensive avoidant functioning","Approximately 60-65%, demonstrating functional distress initially followed by effective maternal soothing","Approximately 90-95%, signifying attachment pathology is exceedingly rare within pediatric populations","Approximately 10%, indicating pervasive relational instability uniformly distributed across environments"], answer:1, difficulty:"medium", rationale:"Correct: (B) In Western samples: ~60-65% secure (Type B), ~20% avoidant (Type A), ~10-15% resistant/ambivalent (Type C), ~10-15% disorganized (Type D, added later). Proportions vary across cultures.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Lower figures clustering near 20% effectively approximate the insecure-avoidant typologies.\n(C) 90-95% erroneously overestimates stable normative secure emotional attachment parameters globally.\n(D) Extremely low single digits severely underrepresents natural secure biological maternal coupling."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Chomsky's Language Acquisition Device (LAD) proposes that:", options:["Human language is entirely exclusively learned through highly specific operant behavioral reinforcement","Humans possess an innate, generalized biological neurological capacity specifically for language acquisition","Comprehensive grammatical language skills can only logically be taught formally within structured classrooms","Primate animal species inherently possess the exact same latent qualitative language capacity as human beings"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Chomsky: children are born with an innate LAD containing universal grammar — the structural rules common to all languages. This explains why children acquire language rapidly, make systematic errors, and produce novel sentences never heard before.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Skinner's distinct radical behavioral operant positions stand entirely opposed; Chomsky aggressively rejected them.\n(C) Standard children fluidly acquire functional native language environments avoiding overt structured formal education.\n(D) Natural human evolutionary language cognitive capacity sits completely isolated and qualitatively radically unique."},
        {domainId:4, q:"Scaffolding is most effective when it targets:", options:["Cognitive developmental tasks positioned significantly far beyond the individual child's latent capability","Specific educational tasks falling completely within the child's dynamic Zone of Proximal Development","Developmental tasks the child has absolutely already functionally mastered without any external assistance","Completely random psychomotor tasks utterly disconnected from the child's established academic trajectory"], answer:1, difficulty:"easy", rationale:"Correct: (B) Scaffolding is optimally effective within the ZPD — the range between independent capability and what can be achieved with guidance. Tasks too easy (already mastered) don't require scaffolding; tasks too difficult (beyond ZPD) can't benefit from it.\n\nWhy others are wrong:\n(A) Educational tasks situated practically beyond latent ZPD capacity routinely render scaffolding fundamentally inert.\n(C) Previously mastered academic components clearly demand no further structured extrinsic adult pedagogical support.\n(D) Effective environmental scaffolding reliably requires systematic intentional trajectory alignment, entirely opposing randomness."}
    ];

    batch45.forEach(q => {
        const domain = EPPPData.domains.find(d => d.id === q.domainId);
        if (domain) {
            domain.questions.push({
                q: q.q, options: q.options, answer: q.answer,
                difficulty: q.difficulty, rationale: q.rationale,
                domainId: q.domainId, domainName: domain.name
            });
        }
    });

    console.log(`PasstheEPPP: Loaded ${batch45.length} additional questions (batch 45).`);
})();
